\\t}\\n\\t\\treturn IdentityTypeEnvironment.INSTANCE;\\n\\t}\\n\\n}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777448807967}}\n1968:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Exploring type environments**\\n\\nI need a generic superclass environment, maybe using getSuperclass to create a CompoundTypeEnvironment for the parent context, along with the class environment. If I have a class like StringArrayHolder that extends GenericArrayHolder<String> and has a field T[] values, I’m wondering how to get the XClass for the subclass. From there, I can retrieve the superclass to check the declared properties and see how T should bind to String. I should examine TypeEnvironmentFactory to clarify this.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0e1d559eae0d8c3c0169f1b7649ec4819fa7dfa5c805c96ae2\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp8bdn84oBtC3zFX-4R4ZGLow7YavKquB64GwCuuJ6AD3JKIELpQsfJ7CctS-pvo7QDIcN2-0q0bL4-R6rl9mjh7dTDx9ci1ziOO8uo2y5I--LlKt9-iDLwAsG6vxYIo__GUD_VmkQ1y0AgpEAOKoNx0n_x4MIx1L7gkN9G505sgjWIsxfm7Kfh6PApMzAzwm1Lz-DCvtR1MMRVrCOZOMtFeBOd2C-VVCfk2n2-uMGwe-mGEhgGNGpTOPx5gecJv8pCn_-KW5V81eR6L7D9TZX2lQJj3NvIT9XIphixgvq5BbN0F5VsQlUeSgeWb30UIksq2nxTz-hUu0h5_t6XWIeZM-TAYKX42227sZF_A5YJjp5z7KQf3hiJqkSaZSj4bmRtHTocosbu3S_j_tKywA54kJ4toePLA3IF3yyPbnOJgpydnsP_tgz4GLKglFZjHR3I5mJZULMDrPAXS_lj26D2Ube_BkehsCda2M39bWMsaSVD16Cfz3eLwwGfobWjU_Q1bWuDIFaq29xPOFrF5nSGo6RaWSbuhzKtJlMNOGug6eh6VoRVCg92Gr1ponGRvUB1cdoUDw84baHcG4j9vbIAW1x97MxARojnPG84tcxmJ-tG6h6mcXBR2BHpbNIc4kEAf1nr4smFGlR2U3nWpunCbfJbdFjwshHNF-L-lTm5rQzu4F6_lRdTdEZSkHqIWUZSA_uFSVqCAYpONS7lDTlJ8fuNxSi8mLCaJxa7CVzScG3eg1X4I11DofzTrwwIvrB8BhTplK1iulvt9GouQumhMecz8FZiIweFv3uhgdYSTE-G9RPBBuL4iT7RjfmWpx5HW11LC9w55QnEbEGJUc808SzNOU6jg4KsxpM7itEm_w1BLx0UfWaXYDQ1RC01elaEaQOUahdS12S3Ev1eC-RhRVfPNx6bKCKZgb5q1t48x9-ygtD_e_xqHz1sRpZgH_zSzrTMvvv6YFbjh93SLQjqbBTDRsBN3lytktANPOnQAH46RFUsM4BoL79q5d18j3RTa0lZ_Oz7JWXFDYn